[[File:Jan Van Beers Vanity Fair 12 September 1891.jpg|thumbnail|right|An 1891 ''Vanity Fair'' caricature of Van Beers titled "The Modern Wiertz".]]
[[File:Jan van Beers posing as Sir Anthony van Dyck.jpg|right|196px|Van Beers posing as [[Sir Anthony van Dyck]].]]
'''Jean Marie Constantin Joseph "Jan" van Beers''' (27 March 1852&nbsp;<U+2013> 17 November 1927) was a Belgian painter and illustrator, the son of the poet [[Jan van Beers]]. They are sometimes referred to as ''Jan van Beers the elder'' and ''Jan van Beers the younger''. In 1884, Van Beers produced the pen-and-ink sketches for the ''edition de luxe'' of his father's poetry.

==Early life==
Van Beers studied at the [[Royal Academy of Fine Arts (Antwerp)|Royal Academy of Fine Arts]] in Antwerp. Soon afterwards, he became the leader of a group of young artists, the <U+201C>Van Beers clique.<U+201D> This group included the artists [[Piet Verhaert]] (1852-1908), [[Alexander Struys]] (1852-1941), and [[Jef Lambeaux]] (1852-1908). They were well-known for their mischievous and eccentric behaviour, including walking around Antwerp dressed in historic costumes.<ref name=RO>{{cite web|title=Jan van Beers, Belgian (1852 - 1927)|url=http://rogallery.com/van_Beers_Jan/van_beers-biography.html|work=rogallery.com|publisher=ROgallery|accessdate=8 March 2014}}</ref>

Van Beers began his career as a [[History painting|history painter]], producing works relating to the Renaissance, for instance ''Funeral of Charles the Good'', which was so large and contained so many figures that van Beers said he only recouped the costs of production despite selling it for 12,000 Francs.<ref name=West/>

==Ladies of Paris==
In 1880 he moved to Paris and immediate abandoned historical pictures, producing instead [[Genre art|genre]] and [[Portrait painting|portrait]] works of the middle classes and developing a successful line in attractive drapped young ladies reading a letter or a book or day-dreaming about a lover. Van Beers said that he wanted to paint what he saw and what was the best and most interesting things that one saw in Paris but her women? He explained in an 1893 interview for the ''[[Westminster Budget]]'' that "all my pictures are from models, and I know where to find them whenever I want them. It requires a good deal of diplomacy to get them to pose. One has to pet and coax them, and even then they often leave you in the lurch."<ref name=West>[http://www.newspapers.com/newspage/34430152/ ''Westminster Budget''] 31 March 1893, p. 22. Retrieved 8 March 2014.</ref> 

''[[Vanity Fair (British magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' showed him with a typical subject in their 1891 caricature titled "The Modern Wiertz" ([[Antoine Wiertz]], 1806-65). Van Beers' work was often compared to that of his Belgian predecessor, particularly the more macabre and grotesque elements. In his novel ''[[Tess of the d'Urbervilles]]'', Thomas Hardy mentions "the staring and ghastly attitudes of a Wiertz Museum and with the leer of a study by Van Beers".<ref name=Wilson>{{cite book|last=Wilson|first=Keith (ed.)|title=A companion to Thomas Hardy|date=2013|publisher=Wiley-Blackwell|location=Hoboken, N.J.|isbn=9781118307496|pages=216-217}}</ref>

