==Controversy and criticism==
Van Beers' work was not always well received and he was sometimes criticised for vulgarity. In 1879, Huysmans described Van Beers' submission to that year's [[Salon (Paris)|Salon]] as "demented colours, absurd and crazy notions, a hotch-potch of ancient and modern mixed up on a single canvas".<ref>Quoted in "BEERS, Jan Marie Constantin van", ''[[Benezit Dictionary of Artists]]''. Oxford Art Online, [[Oxford University Press]], 8 March 2014.</ref>

In 1881, van Beers exhibited two works at the Brussels Salon, both painted in his new hyperrealistic miniature style. One, a painting of the yacht "Sirene", was suspected by the critics Max S<U+00FC>lzberger, Georges De Mons and Lucien Solvay of being a "photo-peinture", a painting created over a photograph. The ''Review de l<U+2019>Art Moderne'' defended van Beers, suggesting that the critics and other artists were jealous of his commercial success.<ref name=RO /><ref name=IN>{{cite web|last=Baetens|first=Jan Dirk|title=Photography in the Picture: Style, Genre and Commerce in the Art of Jan Van Beers (1852-1927)|url=http://www.imageandnarrative.be/inarchive/painting/Jan_Dirk_Baetens.htm|work=imageandnarrative.be|publisher=image & narrative|accessdate=13 March 2014}}</ref> Van Beers suggested that experts could scrape off the paint to determine the truth of the allegations. A semi-official investigation followed, and eventually van Beers started legal proceedings. "L'affaire Van Beers" gave him Europe-wide attention. The eventual report found in his favour and that he was "an honest man". Previously a largely unknown artist, van Beers was able to use his new found fame to sell his work for large sums.<ref name=IN />

